ACUTE RENAL FAILURE). CLINICAL STAGES 1 AND 2 CANNOT BE DETERMINED SOLELY BY CALCULATED GFR. SEE BELOW.

Result Comment: MONOCYTE DISTRIBUTION WIDTH (MDW) IS AN INVITRO DIAGNOSTIC PARAMETER THAT REFLECTS A CHANGE IN CIRCULATING MONOCYTES VOLUME IN RESPONSE TO PRO-INFLAMMATORY SIGNALS FROM INFECTIOUS ORGANISMS.
PERIPHERAL BLOOD MONOCYTE DISTRIBUTION WIDTH AS AN EARLY SEPSIS INDICATOR IN THE BLOOD CELL DIFFERENTIAL HAS THE FOLLOWING LIMITATIONS:
SAMPLES MUST BE COLLECTED IN AN EDTA BLOOD TUBE WITHIN 12 HOURS OF PATIENT PRESENTING TO THE EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS AND MUST NOT BE REFRIGERATED. SPECIMEN MUST BE EVALUATED WITHIN TWO (2) HOURS OF BLOOD COLLECTION.
MICRO-TUBE AND BULLET TUBE SAMPLE COLLECTIONS ARE NOT ACCEPTABLE FOR EVALUATION OF MDW.
MDW IS ONLY REPORTED IN AUTOMATED DIFFERENTIALS, IT IS NOT AVAILABLE IN A MANUALLY PERFORMED CELL DIFFERENTIAL.
MDW IS APPROVED FOR PATIENTS BETWEEN 18 AND 89 YEARS OF AGE. MDW RESULT VALUES OF 20.0 U OR LESS DO NOT RULE OUT SEPSIS. PATIENT VALUES GREATER THAN 20.0 U SHOULD BE CAREFULLY INTERPRETED BY THE PATIENTS PHYSICIAN WITH CONSIDERATION OF OTHER LABORATORY AND CLINICAL FINDINGS.
